column1: Data Supplied By: National Livestock Reporting Service
Data source: National Livestock Reporting Service
Please see terms of use here: https://www.mla.com.au/general/Terms-and-conditions/data-and-information/

Numbers were steady for the second last sale of the year. The quality was good with plenty of feeder steers and heifers and most were heavy weights. Light cattle, under 300kg were in short supply. There was a good number of medium weight heifers to the trade but heavy trade cattle were limited with feeders buying a bit more condition. Grown steers and heifers were well supplied and best supported  by export feeders with prime heavy weights back in volume. The cow were reduced in numbers and there were all weight and grade on offer. The market was stronger.
 
Feeder steers were 15c to 20c dearer with medium and heavy weights ranging from 324c to 402c/kg. Heifers nearly lifted as much as steers and sold from 290c to 357c/kg. Medium weight heifers to the trade were firm 296c to 328c/kg and heavy weights were firm to 3c softer with feeders taking the better breed lines.
 
Export feeders were 15c stronger with most of the 2 and 4 tooth steers selling from 328c to 380c/kg. Prime grown steers and bullocks were 8c to 10c stronger, 310c to 350c/kg and the prime grown heifers lifted at a similar rate selling between 305c and 333c/kg. Cows were 12c to 15c/kg dearer with heavy weights selling from 275c to 302c/kg and the medium weight 2 score cows 250c to 262c/kg.
